WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.960
 So now we're going to talk about a technique called template inheritance.

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:08.920
 And this and other times, it's a great time to review object-oriented programming,

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:13.640
 cuz I'm just gonna like use object-oriented programming definitions and

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:16.480
 words and not completely explain them.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:19.760
 So you gotta know what a class is, you know what self is, those kinds of things.

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:23.800
 And I've got a great online lesson that you can go read and listen to and

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:27.560
 understand objects and I'll explain it to you in 30 or 40 minutes.

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:31.200
 So inheritance actually from that lecture

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.840
 is the notion in object-oriented programming to not repeat yourself.

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:41.200
 You have some kind of a shape and then you make a bunch of objects that mirror

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:45.320
 that shape, but you can also with inheritance you can have a shape that

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:49.320
 makes another shape like a shape in general that's a triangle.

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:52.520
 And so you can inherit that all triangles have everything shapes have and

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:56.080
 all squares have everything shapes have and all circles.

00:00:56.080 --> 00:00:59.920
 And it's just a way of capturing information once,

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:03.080
 writing code once and then not repeating yourself.

00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:08.840
 Functions are a form of DRY, don't repeat yourself, modules are.

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:14.160
 But inheritance is the key and inheritance kinda can get in our way as programmers

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:17.960
 because it leads to smaller and smaller code.

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:22.000
 If we're gonna make five things, each of these five things is really small because

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.920
 we make a big thing over here and we inherit all five of those things from it.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:29.680
 But then you look at it and like, I don't understand that, right?

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:32.960
 I don't understand these only one line functions.

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:33.640
 What are they doing?

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:38.560
 Well, the answer is there's 50 lines out here that we're inheriting from.

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:39.920
 So we'll see some of that.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:45.360
 I'll try to kinda allude to that part where, look, there's magic over there.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:48.200
 And a lot of what you do in Django is use classes and

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:52.200
 objects that you didn't even create, meaning that they've got data in them,

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:55.200
 like .scheme or request.scheme.

00:01:55.200 --> 00:02:01.480
 And so this is just also a way of trying to simplify the way you handle sort of

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:03.360
 things, objects that are handed to you, and

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.600
 then you hand objects to other parts of Django.

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:11.960
 So template rendering basically says, okay,

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:14.160
 here's some rendered data and here's a template.

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:18.600
 What happens now is there's this thing called a base template.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:22.240
 And the base template and the template combine together to be sort of like

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:25.880
 the ultimate template, and then you pass in the rendered data and

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:27.680
 produce the rendered output.

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:32.160
 So let's just say that we had a bunch of pages and

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:34.040
 we were doing the same thing over and over again.

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:37.760
 Now we will soon do this with navigation cuz you wanna put a menu at the top of

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:43.000
 every page and literally that menu could be 40 or 50 lines of HTML.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.720
 And you do not wanna repeat that menu every time at the top of the page.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.880
 So you wanna put that one place and then you wanna make many pages that have

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:54.520
 the same top navigation so that your pages,

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:58.040
 as you go between them, look like the navigation is the same.

00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:00.400
 So we're gonna do this in a very, very simple way.

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:05.040
 So we have one template, this cond.html that we've been playing with.

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:09.280
 You'll notice it has some HTML and a title and a body tag and some of this.

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:11.560
 And then it's got this stuff.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:17.280
 Well, let's say we wanted a bunch of pages that had that everything but the body.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:22.800
 So what we basically then do is we take parts of this,

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:25.720
 like the repeated parts, and we put it into a template.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:32.560
 And then we take the part that we're gonna change every time and

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:35.720
 we put it into a template that then extends.

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:41.360
 So see this one here has one line that says extends temple-based.html.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:46.100
 So this one uses everything in here but then adds some stuff, okay?

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:51.880
 So the basic idea is we split this one big template into reusable parts and

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:53.400
 non-reusable parts.

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:57.200
 And then we have a bunch of templates that come off of base.

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.640
 We call it base, commonly in object-oriented world,

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:02.200
 because it's like the thing that we're basing it on.

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:05.200
 So this is the base and then we're gonna build on it.

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:07.440
 Base builds something else on top of it.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.520
 So how this works in practice, we have a view here.

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:12.680
 We're gonna call this view game two, right?

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:15.400
 So we're gonna use the URL game two.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:16.680
 We have a class-based view.

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:18.400
 We have a get method in there.

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:20.400
 The request data comes in as request.

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:25.420
 We told it to parse the slug off the end and pass it to us in the variable guess.

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:28.880
 We make a template, which is exactly what we did before,

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:32.440
 where we have a key of guess and the value is the actual guess itself.

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:36.240
 And then we pass that template in the variable x into render and

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:41.560
 we tell it to go read temple con two, which is the second conditional one.

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:45.080
 And the thing is, is there's nothing in the Python code,

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:48.240
 in the views.py, that knows about the base.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:53.560
 What happens is the only place that the base is in the,

00:04:53.560 --> 00:04:58.120
 the only place that the base is noted is in the con two template itself.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:01.000
 It says, hey, go grab this one and extend it.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.120
 Now the way it works is it starts out a little counterintuitive.

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:09.360
 It says start with, it really says start with this template here and

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:14.080
 then push this content into the base template.

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:18.280
 And this block content and end block, it basically,

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:23.180
 that tells what I want to replace, you're replacing blocks in the base template.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:28.120
 So all the stuff in the con2.html that is between the block and

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:32.000
 the end block is what is then pushed into the base template.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.760
 And then in a sense, the base template, with those blocks replaced,

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:38.720
 is what is returned as a result of the render and

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:42.500
 then returned to Django as the HTTP response.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:43.640
 We're gonna use these a lot.

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:47.160
 When we start doing navigation, we're gonna go crazy with these things.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:51.120
 So up next, we wanna talk about URL mapping and reversing,

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:55.280
 where we have to actually make a link in one page to a different page.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:05.280
 [MUSIC]

